# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: action-of-11-september-1779
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] The **action of 10 August 1780** was a minor naval engagement that took place off Brest during the American Revolutionary War between a Royal Navy frigate and a French Navy frigate.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] This was the first engagement thought to involve the use of the carronade.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] The 36-gun frigate HMS *Flora* (1780) under Captain William Williams was patrolling off Ushant not far from Brest on the afternoon of 10 August 1780.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] *Flora*, as well as her nominal armament also carried six recently-introduced 18-pounder carronades.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] Through the haze she sighted two vessels, a square-rigged vessel and a cutter, about four miles away.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] As *Flora* approached, the cutter edged away, while the square-rigged vessel waited, accepted battle.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] When the two ships were within two cables length the French ship raised her colours and opened fire.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] Moving in, for over an hour the two frigates battered each other relentlessly; *Flora* being much cut up, moved closer in which the carronades were able to sweep the decks of the French ship with grapeshot.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] After another 15 minutes the French abandoned their guns and attempted to board, but *Flora*'s crew repulsed the attempt.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] An explosion of a box of cartridges aboard the Frenchman added further to the carnage.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] *Flora*'s crew then boarded the French vessel and within moments the French vessel struck.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] She proved to be the frigate *La Nymphe*, pierced for 40 guns, but mounting only 32, and commanded by the Chevalier Charles-Marie de Trolong du Rumain, who died that evening of his wounds with command being passed to Lieutenant Pennandref de Keranstret.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] In the aftermath of *La Nymphe* being taken by *Flora*, the Navy Board quickly became enamoured of the carronade and the weapon’s effectiveness in combat.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-august-1780] As a result they were soon mounted on many Royal Navy ships.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] The **action of 10 September 1782** was a minor engagement between five merchant vessels — four East Indiamen of the British East India Company and a country-ship — on the one side, and a French frigate on the other.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] The action resulted in only a few casualties and was inconclusive.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] What was noteworthy was that the Indiamen sought out the French man-of-war and attacked it; it would have been more usual for the merchantmen to have avoided combat as they had little to gain from a battle.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] Since at least the mid-18th Century, and to a great degree even earlier, the East India Company would annually send a fleet of Indiamen from England to trade with India, South East Asia, and China.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] The vessels would generally, and particularly during wartime, stay together for mutual protection and support to the Cape of Good Hope, and then sail independently, or in smaller groups, to Bombay, Madras, Bengal (Calcutta), and on.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] During wartime the Royal Navy would often provide warships to escort the fleet well into the Atlantic, and possibly as far as St Helena.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] Country ships, i.e., ships based in India, some sailing for the Company, some independent, might join up in India with vessels going on to China, again for mutual protection against pirates, and in wartime privateers and enemy vessels.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] On the homeward journey, the vessels that had gone to China would return in convoy, generally stopping at St Helena to pick up escorts back to England.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] Frequently other vessels, such as whalers returning from the South Seas fisheries, might join at St Helena too.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] The British vessels involved in the action of 9 September 1782 had sailed from Portsmouth on 13 March 1781, bound for Bombay and China as part of a convoy of Indiamen accompanying a British squadron under Commodore George Johnstone.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] At about the same time, a French squadron under the command of Bailli de Suffren left France.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] Both squadrons were sailing for the Cape of Good Hope, the British to take it from the Dutch, the French aiming to help defend it and French possessions in the Indian Ocean, including Rodriguez Island, Ile Bourbon (Réunion), Île de France (Mauritius), and Pondicherry.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] The two squadrons, including the Indiamen, met in the battle of Porto Praya.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] Though the battle was inconclusive, it did enable the French to forestall the British attack on the Cape.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] The British sailed on to the Cape, where Johnstone captured five Dutch East Indiamen at the battle of Saldanha Bay.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] The British Indiamen then sailed on, directly, or indirectly, to India.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] On 8 August 1782 the Indiamen *Asia*, *Essex*, *Locko*, and *Osterley*, and the country ship *Shah Byram Gore*, left Bombay, bound for China.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] The captains were Patrick Lawson of *Locko*, who was the senior captain, Samuel Rodgers of *Osterley*, Robert Maw of *Asia*, Arthur Morris of *Essex*, and Maugham of *Shah Byram Gore*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] As the squadron was sailing through the Strait of Malacca on 6 September, it sighted a Malay vessel at anchor by the shore near Mount Formosa (1°49′N 102°55′E﻿ / ﻿1.817°N 102.917°E﻿ / 1.817; 102.917), some 40 miles southeast of Malacca.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] The captain of the Malay vessel reported that there was a French frigate and two brigs anchored at Pisang Island, and that the captain of the frigate had asked him if he had seen five ships coming from Bombay.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] This intelligence led Lawson to believe that the French were cruising, looking for his squadron, but did not believe themselves stronger than the Indiamen.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] On 9 September the ships encountered the 38-gun French frigate *Pourvoyeuse*, which was under the command of Lieutenant J.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] That evening *Locko* and *Pourvoyeuse* came quite close, but no engagement ensured.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] *Locko* did fire on and take possession of a Malay sloop that he feared the French captain had dispatched to summon the two brigs that had been reported accompanying the frigate.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] The engagement began at 10 minutes past 2 p.m. on 10 September, when *Pourvoyeuse* opened fire with her bow chasers.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] *Locko*, *Osterley*, and *Shah Byram Gore* were closest but withheld their fire.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] When *Pourvoyeuse* fired her broadside at *Locko*, Lawson responded with a broadside.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] The engagement lasted some two-and-a-half hours, with *Locko* and *Osterley* bearing the brunt of it.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] Although *Asia* and *Essex* did fire on *Pourvoyeuse*, Lawson tried to keep them out of the battle as felt they were weakly manned, with a large portion of their crews being lascars.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] Towards dusk, the two opponents separated.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] *Locko* pursued *Pourvoyeuse*, whose two 18-pounder stern guns took away some of *Locko*'s rigging.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] *Pourvoyeuse* extinguished her lights and steered towards Malacca.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] At 8:15 Lawson gave up the chase, which would have taken the squadron in the opposite direction from China, and signalled to his squadron to resume their voyage.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] *Locko* brought up the rear as they sailed, so that should *Pourvoyeuse* wish to resume the action *Locko* would be the first vessel she would encounter.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] On the British side, *Osterley* had two men killed, and *Locko* and *Essex* had several men injured from exploding cartridges.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] *Pourvoyeuse* had four seamen killed, and two officers and several seamen wounded.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] After the return to Britain of the four captains of the Indiamen, the East India Company awarded them prizes.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-10-september-1782] We do not know what Samuel Rogers received, or if Patrick Lawson even received anything as by 1787 he had fled Britain for India to escape a fine of £100,000 for having smuggled goods back to Britain on *Locko*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] The **action of 11 April 1783** was a naval engagement which took place during the American Revolutionary War in the East Indies campaign.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] The French corvette *Naïade* was spotted by the 64-gun HMS *Sceptre*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] In a five hour long fight *Sceptre* captured *Naïade* off Trincomalee on the night of 14 April 1783.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] On 11 April, *Captaine de Brûlot* Louis Thomas Villaret de Joyeuse was given command of *Naïade*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] Admiral Pierre André de Suffren sent her to Madras to warn the French blockading squadron, composed of the 74-gun *Fendant*, the 64-gun *Saint-Michel* and the frigates *Cléopâtre* and *Coventry*, of the imminent arrival of a superior British force.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] Three days after her departure, on 11 April 1783, *Naïade* spotted the 64-gun HMS *Sceptre*, under Captain Samuel Graves.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] In the light of a full moon and with the wind too light to escape and trying without success to elude his much stronger opponent, Villaret was forced into battle.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] At 22:00 the cannonade began and after two hours of resistance as *Sceptre* closed in on *Naïade*, Graves invited Villaret to surrender but the latter flatly refused.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] The fight resumed, but soon *Naïade* began suffering heavy damage.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] After two hours of resistance the French corvette had lost two topmasts, her wheel shot away, seven guns dismounted and her rigging was disabled.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] Villaret seeing that further resistance was futile struck his colours.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] The *Sceptre* had only the mizenmast damaged; casualties were light on both sides, 24 on the Sceptre and 34 on the *Naïade*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] Having admired the fight and the resistance, Graves reportedly returned Villaret de Joyeuses' sword to him.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] The *Naïade* was found to be armed with eighteen to twenty 8-pounder guns and ten swivel guns, and had a crew of 160 men, the latter of which became prisoners of war including Villaret.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] Despite the loss of *Naïade*, the British squadron was unable to locate the French ships, *Sceptre* would next take part in the Battle of Cuddalore against Suffren's fleet two months later.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-april-1783] The British armed *Naïade* with twenty-two 12-pounder guns, and two 18-pounder and six 12-pounder carronade, but never commissioned her.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] The **Action of 11 September 1778** was a minor naval engagement which took place off the French port of Brest during the American War of Independence, between the French frigate *Junon* and the Royal Navy frigate HMS *Fox*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] During the engagement that followed, *Junon* outgunned *Fox* forcing her to strike.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] HMS *Fox*, a twenty eight gun frigate had been under the command of Captain Thomas Windsor, and was sailing off Brest keeping an eye on the French fleet which was then believed to be at sea in the vicinity of Cape Finisterre.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] On 11 September 1778, a lookout on *Fox* sighted two vessels - the latter being the newly commissioned *Junon*; a 32-gun frigate under the command of Captain Antoine-François de Beaumont, the Vicomte de Beaumont Haunt with a crew of some three hundred and thirty men.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] *Fox* gave chase, but the weather made visibility poor and obscured *Junon*'s approach.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] When *Fox* finally sighted *Junon*, *Fox* prepared to engage.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] The two vessels manoeuvred against each other until finally exchanged broadsides at some distance.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] *Junon* then tried to obtain a raking position over the *Fox*, and when this move was thwarted, she attempted to come down from to windward on her opponent's quarter.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] *Junon*s' heavier firepower at short range soon began to tell.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] The *Fox* had lost 14 men killed and 32 wounded.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] The French towed *Fox* into Brest where she was repaired.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] In January 1779 Windsor was allowed to return to England on parole following the intervention in Paris of William Keppel, who desired both men to appear as witnesses at the court-martial of his brother, Augustus Keppel, conversant with the fall-out from the Battle of Ushant.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1778] The *Fox* in French service did not last long, for on 22 March 1779 she was driven aground off Brittany with no hope of salvage.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1779] The **action of 11 September 1779** was a minor naval engagement that took place off Charles Town in the War of the American Independence between the French Navy and the Royal Navy at the Siege of Savannah.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1779] The battle ended with the capture of the British post ship *Ariel* by *Amazone*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1779] On 11 September 1779, whilst the *Ariel* was cruising off Charles Town under Captain Thomas Mackenzie, she sighted a strange sail and approached to investigate, unaware that a French fleet under the Admiral comte d'Estaing had entered the theatre from the West Indies.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1779] As Mackenzie got closer he realized that the stranger was actually a frigate, accompanied by two brigs and a schooner, and that she was not responding to his signals, he had to retreat for the Georgia shore.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1779] The frigate gradually overhauled *Ariel* and Mackenzie was forced to stand and fight.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1779] The enemy vessel was the 36-gun French *Amazone*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1779] The crews of these two vessels then went to man a variety of British vessels on the North America Station.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-11-september-1779] The French took the captured ship into service as *Ariel*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] The **action of 12 August 1782** was a minor single-ship action that opposed the French 32-gun frigate *Bellone* to the British 28-gun HMS *Coventry* in the run-up to the Battle of Trincomalee.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] Although both ships were frigates, *Bellone* belonged to the *Iphigénie* class and was a comparatively large frigate for her time, carrying a battery of 18-pounder long guns, while *Coventry* was a sixth-rate armed only with 9-pounder long guns.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] Furthermore, *Bellone* had the advantage of the wind.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] The nominal crew of *Coventry* was about tho thirds of that of *Bellone*, but in the occasion it was reinforced by the troops she was carrying.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] In spite of these overwhelming odds, *Coventry* managed to inflict heavy casualties on *Bellone*, and most decisively to shoot most of the senior staff.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] The resulting confusion on *Bellone* allowed *Coventry* to escape to Madras.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] The War of American Independence triggered an Anglo-French War from 1778 and, by extension, a Fourth Anglo-Dutch War from 1780 when the Dutch Republic refuse to stop trading with enemies of Britain.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] This aligned French and Dutch interests in the Indian Ocean theatre.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] France had a base of operation at Isle de France (Mauritius) and was allied with Hyder Ali, while the Dutch were holding the Dutch Cape Colony.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] France sent convoys escorted by ships of the line to reinforce these outpost.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] The French consolidated squadrons from Pondicherry, Isle de France and those escorting the convoys into a force numbering 15 ships of the line and several frigates, first under Estienne d'Orves and, after he died, under Suffren.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] This fleet was opposed to an equivalent British force under Admiral Edward Hughes.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] In August 1782, Suffren and Hughes had already fought three inconclusive actions at Sadras on 17 February 1782, Providien on 12 April and Negapatam on 6 July, and were positioning for their fourth encounter at Trincomalee, that was to flare up on 25 August and last until 3 September.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] In late July, Suffren's squadron was at Cuddalore for a high-level meeting with Hyder Ali in neighbouring Bahour.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] Suffren sent his light ships to recon Trincomalee; informed that the British fleet was not in harbour, he decided to sail there himself and land troops and attempt to conquer the city.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] The French squadron left Cuddalore on 2 August 1782 and progressed towards Batacalo.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] Suffren detached *Bellone* with orders to sail first and Batacalo and then Galle, where French captain Aymar was waiting for him with the 74-gun *Illustre*, the 64-gun *Saint Michel* and 8 transports carrying troops and supplies.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] *Bellone* had a new captain, Pierrevert, who was a nephew to Suffren; he had replaced the former captain, Jean André de Pas de Beaulieu, promoted to the command of the 64-gun *Brillant* during Suffren's reshuffling of his captains in the wake of the Battle of Negapatam.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] On 12 August, as the French squadron had arrived at Batacalo and was anchored in the bay, HMS *Coventry* sailed in the South-East of the harbour, ferrying troops to Madras.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] *Vengeur* and *Artésien* attempted to chase to investigate, but soon lost contact and returned to the fleet.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] Meanwhile, *Bellone* had her mainmast damaged by a gust of wind off Ceylon and was sailing to Batacalo for repairs.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] *Bellone* had the advantage of the wind and was a much stronger frigate than *Coventry*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] However, Pierrevert made the mistake of stopping his frigate and letting *Coventry* approach, allowing Mitchell to close to pistol range and open fire with grapeshot and musketry.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] This caused heavy casualties on *Bellone*, and soon mortally wounded Pierrevert himself.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] As the first officer took over, second officer Boucher started arguing that he was the one who should take command, due to a regulation barring foreigners to command French warships, and since the first officer was of Italian origin.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] As they argued, fire from *Coventry* killed Boucher and gravely wounded the first officer.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] The third officer took over but, lacking experience, he failed to gain the confidence of his crew and was unable to prevent *Coventry'*s escape.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] *Bellone* sustained 60 men killed or wounded.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] The battle lasted 2 hours, killing or wounding about 60 French and 50 British.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] *Coventry*, her rigging badly damaged, limped back to Madras.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] Hughes had hoped to set sail around 15 August, but it was not until 22 that he was ready to depart.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] The delay allowed Suffren to lay siege to Trincomalee, where Fort Ostenburg fell on 30.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-august-1782] Suffren restored Beaulieu as captain of *Bellone*, and replaced him on *Brillant* with Lieutenant de Kersauson.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] The **action of 12 December 1782** was a naval engagement fought off the coast of Spain near Ferrol, in which the British 40-gun fifth rate HMS *Mediator* successfully attacked a convoy of five armed ships.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] *Mediator* succeeded in capturing one American privateer, the *Alexander*, and then captured the French ex-ship of the line *La Ménagère*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] The convoy was part of Pierre-Augustin de Beaumarchais' supply chain to the American colonists.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] French diplomat Pierre-Augustin de Beaumarchais founded a commercial enterprise, Roderigue Hortalez and Co., supported by France and Spain.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] The French and Spanish supplied the American rebels with weapons, munitions, clothes, and provisions that would never be paid for.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] Beaumarchais contracted for the transport of the supplies in convoys.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] Even so, the Royal Navy captured many of the transport vessels.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] Beaumarchais assembled one convoy in December 1782.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] He met his captains in Bordeaux and then supervised the loading of his vessels.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] The plan was to sail for Port-au-Prince, Saint Domingue and then on to America to supply the American colonists.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] On 9 December 1782 the convoy sailed from the mouth of the Gironde for the West Indies and from there America.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] On 12 December, at 7:00am, HMS *Mediator*, under the command of James Luttrell, was sailing off Ferrol when she sighted the convoy.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] At 8am the convoy formed in line of battle.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] Notwithstanding this formidable array, Captain Luttrell continued bearing down and at 10:00am *Ménagère* initiated the action.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] Luttrell saw that the shot came from the upper deck only and rightly concluded that the French vessel had no lower-deck guns.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] *Mediator* bore up in order to bring the rear ship to action.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] At 10:30am *Mediator* opened fire on *Dauphin Royal* when that ship and the *Alexander* bore up out of the line.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] *Aimable Eugénie*, *Ménagère* and the American brig then wore and endeavored to protect the two rear ships.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] At 3pm the *Aimable Eugénie* hauled off the wind in full sail.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] At 5p.m. he got within gunshot of *Ménagère* and started a running fight.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] At 9:00pm *Mediator*, having got up with the *Ménagère*, was on the point of firing a full broadside.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] Before she could do so *Ménagère* struck.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] Because the enemy fired high in an attempt to damage *Mediator'*s rigging, she sustained no casualties.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] *Ménagere* had four men killed and seven or eight wounded.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] *Alexandre* had six killed and eight or nine wounded.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] Despite being well-treated, Captain Gregory organized a party of the prisoners in an attempt to gain possession of *Mediator*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] He was subdued but then unsuccessfully attempted to set fire to the ship.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] After this Luttrell had Gregory and the American prisoners placed in irons.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] Although the French officers played no part in the attempt, the British also guarded them more closely.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] Michael Seymour, who was later to be a rear admiral, served as a midshipman in HMS *Mediator*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] Luttrell and his crew received the last of the prize money for *Alexandre* and *Ménagere* in October 1788.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-12-december-1782] The action was the final clash of arms in which American forces were engaged before the Treaty of Paris concluded the war.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] The **action of 13 August 1780** was a minor naval battle fought off the Old Head of Kinsale (County Cork, Ireland) in which the 64-gun French "private man of war" (privateer) *Comte d'Artois* fought two British Royal Navy ships, *Bienfaisant* and *Charon*, during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] After Royal Navy admiral George Rodney successfully brought relief to the defenders of Gibraltar, capturing a Spanish convoy off Cape Finisterre and eight days later winning the Battle of Cape St.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] Vincent, his fleet returned to Britain in March 1780.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] One of the ships of his fleet, HMS *Bienfaisant*, under John MacBride, sailed back with them and kept a watch of the Irish coast in order to report if there were any movements by Spanish and French fleets in the area.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] Reports arrived in early August 1780 of a large French privateer, the 64-gun *Comte d'Artois*, which had sailed from Brest to cruise off the Irish south coast, and was at once to be dealt with.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] MacBride was ordered to sail together with the 44-gun HMS *Charon* to capture *Comte d'Artois*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] After several days in search of the vessel, a mysterious sail was finally sighted early on 13 August, chasing after some of the ships of a British convoy departing from Cork.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] MacBride ranged up and fell in with the unidentified ship, which hoisted English colours.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] Both ships came within pistol shot, and it was not until there was some communication between the two ships, that MacBride could be satisfied of her identity.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] By now the two ships were so close, with *Bienfaisant* off the *Comte d'Artois*'s bow, that neither ship could bring their main guns to bear.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] Instead both ships opened fire with muskets until MacBride could manoeuvre away and a general action ensued.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] After an hour and ten minutes the French vessel surrendered.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] She proved to be the *Comte D'Artois,* a private ship of war, mounting 64 guns, and with a crew of 644 men Closnard's command.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] Of his crew, 21 men were killed and 35 wounded.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] *Bienfaisant* had three men killed and 20 wounded.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] *Charon* had only joined the action towards the end of the engagement and only had a single man wounded.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] Two British frigates, *Licorne* and *Hussar*, also came up towards the end of the action and so shared in the prize money with *Bienfaisant* and *Charon*.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] The Royal Navy did not take *Comte d'Artois* into service.
[src:action-of-11-september-1779/action-of-13-august-1780] The capture had an unusual sequel, as just over a year later and under a different captain, *Bienfaisant* captured another privateer, this time named *Comtesse d'Artois*.
